    while (where &lt; numlist &amp;&amp; id &gt; list[where].id) where++;

    if (list[where].id == id)
    {
        …

If `where == numlist` at the end of the while loop (because the element specified by `id` wasn&#39;t found), then `list[where]` is an invalid position in the array and it&#39;s unsafe to inspect `list[where].id`.

Better:

    while (where &lt; numlist &amp;&amp; id &gt; list[where].id)
        where++;

    if ((where &lt; numlist) &amp;&amp; (list[where].id == id))
    {


But that&#39;s probably not your only bug.

You didn&#39;t say whether or not the array was definitively sorted.  Nor did you indicate whether `numlist` is supposed to be after the function returns.

My take is to assume the list is not sorted.  And that `numlist` should reflect the new size of the list.  In the case of removal, that would be `numlist = numlist - 1`.  Here&#39;s a simpler approach:

    void deletelist(listtype list[], int&amp; numlist, int id, ofstream&amp; outf)
    {
        int where = -1;
    
        // find the element
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; numlist; i++)
        {
            if (id == list[i].id)
            {
                where = i;
